 159   
 160      The session can be configured using the SetParameter() method. However, 
 161      sometimes when a certain parameter is modified, some code needs to run in 
 162      response. For example, if the filename is modified, the profile must be 
 163      recalculated. 
 164   
 165      It is not sufficient to attach setter methods to every such parameter 
 166      though, because there is no guarantee which order these parameters are 
 167      configured. For example, suppose we want to set both the filename and the 
 168      profile: 
 169   
 170      session.SetParameter("filename", filename) 
 171      session.SetParameter("profile", "nt/...") 
 172   
 173      Since the profile is explicitly set we should not guess it, but if a simple 
 174      set hook is used, there is no way for the _set_filename() hook to determine 
 175      that the profile is explicitly given. So what will happen now is that the 
 176      filename will be changed, then a profile will be autodetected, then it will 
 177      be immediately overwritten with the user set profile. 
 178   
 179      To avoid this issue we use a context manager to essentially group 
 180      SetParameter() calls into an indivisible unit. The hooks are all run _after_ 
 181      all the parameters are set: 
 182   
 183      with session: 
 184          session.SetParameter("filename", filename) 
 185          session.SetParameter("profile", "nt/...") 
 186   
 187      Now the _set_filename() hook can see that the profile is explicitly set so 
 188      it should not be auto-detected.

 191      configuration parameters. Then, when exiting the context manager we ensure 
 192      that those parameters with hooks are called. The hooks are passed the newly
